      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Distance Signal</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>proximity factor</strong> is the geographic distance between a searcher's detected location and a business's listed address — one of Google's three core local ranking signals, alongside relevance and prominence. Closer businesses rank higher in local pack results by default, with the effect strongest for generic "near me" queries and weakest for brand-specific searches.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Signal type</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Distance-based</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Key update</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Vicinity (Nov 2021)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every local search produces a different result depending on where the searcher is standing. That's the proximity factor at work. You can have more reviews, a better website, and stronger local links — and still lose to a competitor standing a block closer to the person searching. Understanding what you're up against is what separates tactical local SEO from guesswork.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the proximity factor in local SEO?</h2>
        <p>The proximity factor measures how far a business is from the searcher's location at the moment of the query. Google combines this distance measurement with two other local signals to produce local pack rankings:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Relevance</strong> — how well the business matches what the searcher is looking for</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence</strong> — how well-known and authoritative the business is online (reviews, links, citations)</li>
          <li><strong>Proximity</strong> — how close the business is to the searcher's physical location</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Google detects a searcher's location via GPS (mobile), IP address (desktop), and account settings. For "near me" queries, the distance is measured from the searcher. For explicit location queries like "plumber in Austin," Google uses the geographic centre of the named area.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's Vicinity Update — November 2021</div>
          <p>The Vicinity Update significantly increased proximity's weight relative to prominence. Sterling Sky's analysis documented major ranking shifts: businesses closer to the searcher displaced higher-profile competitors located further away. If your local rankings dropped in late 2021, proximity displacement was likely the cause.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the proximity factor matters for your local rankings</h2>
        <p>Proximity creates a structural ranking disadvantage that no amount of review generation or content production can fully overcome at extreme distances. Here's why every local SEO strategy has to account for it:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Your ranking radius is centred on your address.</strong> Visibility in the local pack forms a radius around your physical address. Strength is highest at the centre and decays as the searcher moves further away.</li>
          <li><strong>New competitors can displace you by moving closer.</strong> A newer business with fewer reviews that opens two blocks from your target customer base can leapfrog your rankings for that area overnight.</li>
          <li><strong>Service area businesses face a hidden disadvantage.</strong> SABs rank from their hidden registered address — meaning their proximity signal is anchored to wherever their office or home address is listed, not where they serve customers.</li>
          <li><strong>Query type changes how much proximity matters.</strong> Generic queries ("pizza") are highly proximity-sensitive. Branded or specific queries ("Domino's" or "emergency commercial plumbing") weight relevance and prominence more heavily.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google measures and applies the proximity factor</h2>
        <p>Google's proximity calculation is straightforward but has several nuances that affect how it plays out in practice.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># How Google determines distance</span><br>
          Searcher location <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">GPS / IP / Account settings</span><br>
          Business location <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">GBP registered address</span><br>
          Distance <span class="uf-arrow">=</span> <span class="uf-new">straight-line distance between the two points</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Query modifier changes the reference point</span><br>
          "near me" <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">searcher's exact location</span><br>
          "in [city]" <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">geographic centre of named area</span>
        </div>

        <p>Distance alone doesn't determine position. Google weights proximity differently based on the query type, industry, and competitive landscape. In dense urban markets, even 0.5 miles can separate a local pack position 1 from position 7. In rural markets, the effective ranking radius can stretch to 20+ miles.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Proximity factor vs relevance vs prominence — which wins?</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Signal</th><th>What it measures</th><th>Most influential for</th><th>Can you control it?</th></tr>
            </thead>
