              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Relevance</strong></td><td>Category and content match</td><td>Specific service queries</td><td>Yes — GBP optimisation</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Prominence</strong></td><td>Reviews, links, authority</td><td>Brand queries</td><td>Yes — review + link building</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real proximity factor examples</h2>
        <p>Here are two scenarios that show how proximity plays out in practice:</p>

        <h3>Example 1 — Two pizza shops with different profiles</h3>
        <p>Pizza Shop A (4.2 stars, 150 reviews) at 0.3 miles from the searcher routinely beats Pizza Shop B (4.8 stars, 400 reviews) at 1.2 miles away for "pizza near me." Proximity outweighs prominence at short distances, particularly after the Vicinity Update. Shop B's stronger review profile would need to be combined with other relevance signals to bridge the gap.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — A plumber extending their ranking radius</h3>
        <p>A plumbing business used geo grid rank tracking and discovered strong rankings within 5 miles of their office but almost no visibility on the west side of the city. By publishing neighbourhood-specific content pages, building citations mentioning west-side suburbs, and earning reviews that referenced those areas, they extended their effective ranking radius from 5 miles to 8 miles over 3-6 months.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Proximity factor vs geo grid rank tracking — understanding the connection</h2>
        <p>Geo grid rank tracking is the measurement tool that makes the proximity factor visible. Without it, you can only see your "average" ranking — which blends together strong central positions with weak outlying positions into a meaningless number.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Geo grid reveals</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Exact ranking at dozens of coordinate points</li>
              <li>Where your proximity advantage starts to decay</li>
              <li>Competitor positions relative to your location</li>
              <li>Which neighbourhoods need targeted content</li>
              <li>Before/after impact of local SEO work</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Average rank hides</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Geographic distribution of rankings</li>
              <li>Proximity weak spots in your service area</li>
              <li>Competitors encroaching from specific directions</li>
              <li>Which local content investments are paying off</li>
              <li>SAB ranking centre vs service coverage</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for managing the proximity factor</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Choose your registered address strategically.</strong> Your GBP address is the anchor of your local ranking radius. For brick-and-mortar businesses, locate as close to the highest-density searcher population as possible. For SABs, register at the address that centres your service area.</li>
          <li><strong>Offset proximity disadvantage with stronger relevance.</strong> Use precise, specific GBP categories. Add attributes and services that match the exact queries you need to rank for. A more relevant business can outrank a closer one when proximity alone can't decide the outcome.</li>
          <li><strong>Build local content that references underserved areas.</strong> Neighbourhood-specific landing pages, locally-cited blog content, and service pages mentioning specific suburbs extend your topical relevance into areas where your proximity signal is weaker.</li>
          <li><strong>Generate reviews that mention service locations.</strong> Reviews containing geographic references ("They came to our Westside office in 30 minutes") provide proximity-adjacent relevance signals that partially compensate for physical distance.</li>
          <li><strong>Use geo grid tracking to prioritise effort.</strong> Don't spread local SEO investment uniformly. Identify specific grid cells where you're ranking 4-10 and concentrate link building, content, and citation efforts there first.</li>
          <li><strong>Track results over 3-6 months.</strong> Proximity-based ranking changes take time. Local SEO results from content and citation work compound over quarters, not weeks. Set a 6-month measurement window before evaluating strategy changes.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — trying to beat proximity with reviews alone</div>
          <p>More reviews help, but post-Vicinity Update, proximity has more weight than it did in 2020. A business 3 miles closer to the searcher needs to be outclassed on both relevance and prominence simultaneously for you to rank above them. Build all three signals in combination, not just the easiest one to generate.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common proximity factor mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Registering a GBP address in a low-traffic area</strong> — saves rent but permanently limits your ranking centre, costing more in lost organic visibility than the rent savings.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a virtual office address in a city centre</strong> — Google detects bulk-registered virtual office addresses and may suspend listings or reduce their ranking weight.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring SAB address strategy</strong> — service area businesses that register from a home address on the city outskirts lose proximity signal for the entire urban core they serve.</li>
          <li><strong>Checking rankings from your own office</strong> — your results are biased by your proximity to your own business. Use geo grid tools or incognito mode with location spoofing.</li>
          <li><strong>Conflating average rank with local visibility</strong> — a position 2 average can hide position 8+ for 40% of your service area. Always measure at the coordinate level.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
